com.camerontec.util.datamodel.fix

Class UTCDateTimeDecoder

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.camerontec.util.datamodel.fix.UTCDateTimeDecoder

  • public final class UTCDateTimeDecoder
extends Object
    Utility methods for decoding UTC date, time and combined date/time quantities.

    The methods in this class are designed to be used in place of the standard Java java.text.DateFormat when better performance and/or the ability to decode high precision timestamps (i.e. > millisecond precision) are expected.

    A UTC date is assumed to be of the format 'yyyyMMdd' without variation.

    A UTC time (and also the time part of a combined date/time) is assumed to be in one of the following formats:

    • 'HH:mm:ss' (second precision)
    • 'HH:mm:ssZ' (second precision in UTC timezone)
    • 'HH:mm:ss[+|-HH[:mm]]' (second precision in non UTC timezone)
    • 'HH:mm:ss.SSS' (millisecond precision)
    • 'HH:mm:ss.SSSZ' (millisecond precision in UTC timezone)
    • 'HH:mm:ss.SSS[+|-HH[:mm]]' (millisecond precision in non UTC timezone)
    • 'HH:mm:ss.SSSSSS' (microsecond precision)
    • 'HH:mm:ss.SSSSSSZ' (microsecond precision in UTC timezone)
    • 'HH:mm:ss.SSSSSS[+|-HH[:mm]]' (microsecond precision in non UTC timezone)
    • 'HH:mm:ss.SSSSSSSSS' (nanosecond precision)
    • 'HH:mm:ss.SSSSSSSSSZ' (nanosecond precision in UTC timezone)
    • 'HH:mm:ss.SSSSSSSSS[+|-HH[:mm]]' (nanosecond precision in non UTC timezone)

    All cases above have one byte separators between the various time components, however, those bytes are always just skipped and not validated.

    A combined date/time is expected to be a UTC date, followed by a single byte separator, followed by one of the above UTC times. The separator byte is skipped over and not validated.

    See Also:
    UTCDateDecoderListener, UTCTimeDecoderListener, UTCDateTimeDecoderListener
